  "prompt": "Why does acetone break down cell membranes?",
  "response": "Acetone breaks down cell membranes due to its chemical properties:\n\n1. Solvent properties\n- Acetone is a highly polar organic solvent\n- It can dissolve lipids and disrupt lipid bilayer structure\n- Breaks hydrogen bonds between membrane phospholipids\n\n2. Membrane composition\n- Cell membranes are primarily composed of phospholipids\n- Phospholipids have hydrophilic heads and hydrophobic tails\n- Acetone disrupts the hydrophobic interactions between lipid tails\n\n3. Molecular mechanism\n- Acetone molecules can intercalate between phospholipid molecules\n- This weakens van der Waals forces holding membrane together\n- Causes membrane destabilization and eventual rupture\n\n4. Protein denaturation\n- Acetone can also disrupt protein structures within membranes\n- Breaks hydrogen bonds and alters protein configurations\n- Further compromises membrane integrity\n\n5. Rapid penetration\n- Small, non-polar acetone molecules easily pass through membranes\n- Quickly spreads and causes widespread membrane disruption\n\nThese properties make acetone an effective solvent for breaking down cell membranes, which is why it's used in various scientific and industrial processes involving cell disruption.",
